text: MR LUMBAR SPINE       Reason for Exam: PROGRESSIVELY WORSENING RT SIDED LOWER BACK AND RT LEG BURNING PAIN      TECHNICAL: Routine sagittal and axial T1 and T2.     COMPARISON: Radiographs December 3, 2012     FINDINGS:       There are 4 nonrib-bearing lumbar type vertebra.       Lumbar alignment is normal.       Marrow signal is normal aside from mild discogenic endplate signal change       The visualized portion of the spinal cord is normal in signal and morphology.  The conus appears to terminate at the L1 level.     There is mild lumbar epidural lipomatosis with prominent fat noted at L2, L3-L4 and S1      Visualized extraspinal structures are unremarkable.     At L1-2 and the superior visualized levels there is no significant spinal canal or neuroforaminal stenosis.     L2-L3: Loss of disc height with marginal disc osteophyte complex, and mild epidural lipomatosis.  Mild foraminal stenosis.  There is moderate effacement of the left lateral recess by disc material.  No significant central zone spinal canal stenosis     L3-L4: Loss of disc height with marginal disc osteophyte complex, and epidural lipomatosis.  Mild narrowing of the thecal sac.  Mild effacement of the lateral recesses.  Mild foraminal stenosis.     L4-S1: Loss of disc height with marginal disc osteophyte complex, and epidural lipomatosis.  Disc osteophyte complex is present eccentric to the right involving the right paracentral and foraminal zones and extending far laterally.  Small central zone annular tear is present.  There is no significant central zone spinal canal stenosis.  There is no significant effacement of the left lateral recess or significant left foraminal stenosis.  There is moderate right foraminal stenosis.  The expected right L5 nerve root is contacted far laterally by disc osteophyte complex.  There is moderate effacement of the right lateral recess with posterior displacement of the transversing right S1 nerve root.     IMPRESSION:      Please note that there are only 4 nonrib-bearing lumbar type vertebra.  Careful correlation with imaging is needed if there is to be procedural intervention.     At the L4-S1 level degenerative changes combined with epidural lipomatosis result in effacement of the right lateral recess with posterior displacement of the right S1 nerve root.  As well there is moderate right foraminal stenosis and the right exited L5 nerve root is contacted far laterally by disc osteophyte complex.     At L2-3 disc material results in moderate effacement of the left lateral recess.

PROCEDURE NAME(S):    MR L-SPINE NO CONTRAST    HISTORY:   L5/SI RT DISK SEE CT 10/09/2019 ( ATTACHED )                       REPURTED ? L5 APART DISK                    Lumbar spine MR       Sagittal T1 and T2-weighted images through the entire lumbar region were obtained and axial T1 and T2-weighted images extending   from L2 to the upper sacrum were obtained.  Comparison is made with the recent CT dated 7/10/2019       The spinal cord ends at the L1-2 level.  No lesions involving the distal cord are noted.       No focal disc protrusion, central or intervertebral foramen spinal stenosis in the upper lumbar region or at the L3-4 level is   evident.       At L4-5, mild diffuse disc bulging is evident with no significant focal disc protrusion, central or intervertebral foramen spinal  stenosis.       At L5-S1, mild diffuse disc bulging is evident and there is a moderate-sized broad-based right sided focal disc protrusion which   displaces the right S1 nerve root posteriorly and is associated with mild right intervertebral foramen spinal stenosis.  No   central or left intervertebral foramen spinal stenosis is evident.       Disc degenerative disease is evident with decreased T2 signal in the lower 2 lumbar discs.  No abnormalities of the apophyseal   joints are evident.       IMPRESSION:    1.  Minor bulging L4-5 disc with no focal protrusion    2.  Moderate-sized broad-based right L5-S1 disc protrusion with mild right L5-S1 intervertebral foramen spinal stenosis    3.  Disc degenerative disease

MRI Lumbar Spine without Contrast  CLINICAL DATA: 69 years Female; right L4 radiculopathy  COMPARISON: None.  TECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the lumbar spine was performed  without contrast.  FINDINGS:  Vertebral body heights are maintained. Trace anterolisthesis of L3 on L4. Mild  anterolisthesis of L4 on L5 is degenerative, measuring 7 mm. Mildly heterogeneous  marrow signal.  Multilevel degenerative disc disease is severe at L1-L2 and L4-L5. Multilevel facet  osteoarthritis, severe on the left L4-L5 and L5-S1.  T12-L1: No significant disc bulge, spinal canal stenosis, or neuroforaminal stenosis.  L1-L2: No significant spinal canal stenosis. There is posterior disc osteophyte complex.  Mild bilateral foraminal stenosis due to disc bulge and facet osteophyte.  L2-L3: No significant disc bulge, spinal canal stenosis, or neuroforaminal stenosis.  L3-L4: No significant spinal canal stenosis. Small circumferential disc bulge, without  significant neural foraminal stenosis or definite nerve root impingement in the  subarticular zones.  L4-L5: Moderate to severe spinal canal stenosis due to anterolisthesis with uncovering  disc bulge and severe ligamentum flavum thickening. Severe left and moderate right  foraminal stenosis due to disc bulge and facet osteophyte.  L5-S1: No significant spinal canal stenosis. No significant neural foraminal stenosis.  Nerve roots and visualized distal cord are unremarkable. No fluid collection or mass  within the spinal canal.  Paraspinous soft tissues are unremarkable.  Incompletely visualized 2.5 cm cortical cyst arising from the upper pole left kidney.  IMPRESSION:  Multilevel degenerative disc disease, severe at L4-L5 with mild anterolisthesis of L4 and  L5. There is moderate to severe acquired spinal canal stenosis at L4-L5.  Severe left and moderate right neural foraminal stenosis at L4-L5.  Fluid between the L4-L5 spinous processes, suspicious for adventitial  bursitis/Baastrup's disease (i.e. inflammation related to kissing spinous processes).

MRI LUMBAR SPINE:       Exam is compared to the previous study from 2018.  Lowest major intravertebral disc space has been labeled L5-S1.  Moderate   curvature of the lumbar spine noted apex to the left similar to prior.  Discogenic changes noted at multiple endplates but no   concerning marrow abnormality identified. The conus medullaris is normally located. Paraspinal musculature and partially   visualized retroperitoneal structures normal.       At the T9-10 level, minimal disc bulge impresses mildly on the thecal sac but does not affect the cord.  Mild degenerative   changes at T10-11 and T11-12 also noted with minimal disc bulge but no spinal stenosis or nerve root impingement.       T12-L1:  No significant disc bulge or herniation identified.  Spinal canal and neural foramen are widely patent.. There is mild   facet degenerative change present.       L1-2: Degenerative changes with complete loss of disc height and posterior disc osteophyte complex.  Moderate facet degenerative   changes are present.  Mild impression on the thecal sac but no significant spinal stenosis.  There is narrowing of the left neural  foramen secondary to the degenerative changes and curvature but nerve root is not convincingly impinge upon.         L2-3: Complete loss of disc space with posterior osteophytes. Moderate degenerative changes are noted in the facet joints.    Spinal canal widely patent and no convincing nerve root impingement.       L3-4: Degenerative disc disease with decreased height of the disc and small osteophytes with an diffuse disc bulge.. There is   severe facet degenerative change present.  No spinal stenosis and no nerve root impingement.  Mild narrowing of the right neural   foramen.       L4-5: Severe facet degenerative changes.  There is approximately 6 mm of anterolisthesis of L4 on L5.. Ligamentum flavum   hypertrophy and diffuse disc bulge in combination with the facet degenerative changes and spondylolisthesis do result in   impression on the thecal sac.  There is moderate spinal stenosis present with no surrounding CSF on today's exam.  Severe   narrowing of the right neural foramen and right lateral recess also present.       L5-S1: Very minimal anterolisthesis of L5 on S1 similar to prior.  Severe facet degenerative changes left greater than right with  ligamentum flavum hypertrophy.  No spinal stenosis.  Narrowing of the left neural foramen but no convincing nerve root   impingement..       IMPRESSION:       Findings are similar to on the prior exam.  Severe facet degenerative changes at the L4-5 level with diffuse disc bulge and   spondylolisthesis result in moderate spinal stenosis on today's exam.  There is severe narrowing of the right neural foramen and   right lateral recess.       Otherwise multilevel degenerative disc disease and facet degenerative changes but no convincing spinal stenosis or nerve root   impingement.

Reason for Exam: INVOLVED IN MVC NOVEMBER, 2018,  ONGOING NECK PAIN WITH RADICULAR SYMPTOMS INTO RIGHT UPPER ARM/CHEST.  ?NERVE IMPINGEMENT     TECHNIQUE: Routine unenhanced MRI of the cervical spine.     FINDINGS:  Mild degenerative retrolisthesis at C5-C6 measuring 4 mm. Alignment is otherwise maintained. Vertebral body heights are preserved. Moderate disc height loss and endplate remodeling noted at C5-6. Vertebral hemangioma of C7 on the right. No suspicious bone marrow abnormality. Craniocervical junction is normal. Cervical cord is normal in caliber and signal. Syrinx is suspected within the upper thoracic spinal cord, which is partially imaged and only seen at the inferior most margin of the sagittal images. Incidental 1.5 cm round, circumscribed, T2 hyperintense, T1 hypointense lesion along the left aspect of T3 vertebral body which could represent a foregut duplication cyst, perineural cyst, or a nerve sheath tumor.     C2-C3: Normal.  C2-C4: Normal.  C4-C5: Normal.  C5-C6: Disc osteophyte complex resulting in moderate spinal canal stenosis and severe left and moderate right foraminal stenosis.  C6-C7: Small disc bulge. Spinal canal and neural foramina are patent.  C7-T1: Normal.     IMPRESSION:  1. Disc osteophyte complex at C5-6 associated with moderate spinal canal stenosis and severe left and moderate right foraminal stenoses.  2. Suspected syrinx of the upper thoracic cord, partially imaged. Additionally there is a paravertebral lesion at the left of T3 which could represent a foregut duplication cyst, perineural cyst, or a nerve sheath tumor. Recommend dedicated MRI of the thoracic spine for further evaluation of these findings.

Reason for Exam: SHE HAS SPINAL STENOSIS AND RADICULOPATHY. SHE IS KNOWN WITH CP. SHE WAS SUPPOSED TO GO FOR BACK SURGERY IN 2017. BUT SHE GOT SICK. ?SPINAL STENOSIS      HISTORY:  As above.     TECHNIQUE:  Standard radiculopathy protocol, consisting of sagittal T1 and T2 imaging from T9 to the upper sacrum and axial T1 and T2 imaging from L3-4 to L5-S1.     FINDINGS:  Comparison made to the MR lumbar spine from April 26, 2016 (Grey Nuns Hospital). Lumbar spine x-rays performed December 5, 2016 (St. Paul HCC) and CT abdomen/pelvis from August 27, 2018 (Cold Lake HCC) were also reviewed.     Five lumbar vertebrae are assumed. Moderate curvature of the lumbar spine convex right centered at L3-4. Vertebral body heights are maintained. No focal destructive osseous lesions.     The lower thoracic spinal cord and conus medullaris are suboptimally assessed due to motion artifact. They appear grossly normal in caliber. Conus terminates in a normal fashion at the L1 level. No fatty filum terminale.     Hypointense T2 signal noted within most of the lower thoracic and lumbar discs, indicative of underlying disc degeneration.     Similar tiny posterior disc protrusions are present at the T9-10, T10-11 and T11-12 levels, indenting the thecal sac but not affecting the spinal cord or nerve roots. No spinal stenosis or significant neural foraminal narrowing at these levels.     At T12-L1, disc height is preserved. Mild annular disc bulging is present. No nerve root impingement, spinal stenosis or neural foraminal stenosis. Minor facet degenerative changes.     At L1-2, there is similar subtle retrolisthesis of L1 on L2. Mild loss of disc height eccentrically towards the right. A small right paracentral disc-osteophyte complex indents the thecal sac but does not affect the conus. Moderate stenosis of the right neural foramen noted. No stenosis of the left neural foramen. No spinal stenosis. Minor facet degenerative changes. Appearances are not significantly changed.     At L2-3, disc height is reasonably well-maintained. A small broad-based posterior disc-osteophyte complex indents the ventral thecal sac and encroaches upon the inferior aspects of both neural foramina, resulting in bilateral neural foraminal stenoses of mild to moderate severity. Mild to moderate left-sided and minor right-sided facet degenerative changes. Slight narrowing of the left lateral recess. No stenosis of the right lateral recess. No spinal stenosis. Appearances are not significantly changed.     At L3-4, there remains moderate loss of disc height laterally towards the left with associated moderately advanced degenerative endplate changes. Moderate left-sided and mild right-sided facet degenerative changes and mild ligamentum flavum thickening also noted. A small broad-based disc-osteophyte complex indents the ventral thecal sac. Moderate stenosis of the left lateral recess and moderate to severe narrowing of the left neural foramen noted. Minor narrowing of the right neural foramen. Right lateral recess remains normal in caliber. No significant spinal stenosis. Appearances overall are not significantly changed.     At L4-5, disc height is well-maintained. Bilateral moderate to severe facet degenerative changes are present with ligamentum flavum thickening. A small broad-based posterior disc-osteophyte complex indents the ventral thecal sac. A 6 mm circumscribed focus of hyperintense T1 and T2 signal situated along the anteromedial aspect of the right facet joint is unchanged. This corresponds to a either a small focus of ossification or calcified synovial cyst on the CT scan, contributing to moderate to severe right lateral recess stenosis. There is mild transverse narrowing of the thecal sac posteriorly. No significant left lateral recess narrowing. Mild stenoses of both neural foramina. Appearances overall are similar to the prior MR study.     At L5-S1, there is grade 1-2 spondylolisthesis of 6 mm, worse compared to the 2016 study. Disc height is reasonably well-maintained. There is unroofing of the posterior disc margin, with a small shallow disc bulge indenting the ventral thecal sac. There is severe degeneration of the left facet joint, with severe joint space narrowing and adjacent sclerosis and bony overgrowth evident. Moderate degeneration of the right facet joint also noted. Unilateral right-sided spondylolysis of L5 is again evident. Combination of these findings results in bilateral lateral recess stenoses of at least moderate severity and moderate spinal stenosis. There is severe stenosis of the right neural foramen with virtually complete effacement of the perineural fat and compression and flattening of the exiting right L5 nerve root. Moderate to severe stenosis of the left neural foramen also noted.     Mild degenerative changes noted within the visualized sacroiliac joints. Prevertebral soft tissues are unremarkable.     OPINION:  1. Spondylolisthesis of L5 on S1 is slightly worse compared to the 2016 MR examination. Anterolisthesis is secondary to a combination of right L5 spondylolysis and bilateral facet degeneration. Facet degeneration is severe on the left side. There is severe stenosis of the right L5-S1 neural foramen with compression of the exiting right L5 nerve root. Moderate to severe stenosis of the left neural foramen, bilateral lateral recess stenoses of moderate severity and moderate spinal stenosis at this level also.     2. Multilevel degenerative disc disease in the remainder of the spine is of similar severity, as detailed above. Moderate to severe stenosis of the right lateral recess at L4-5 secondary to a combination of disc degeneration, facet degeneration and small focus of ossification (or synovial cyst with peripheral calcification) at the anteromedial aspect of the right facet joint. Spinal stenosis of moderate severity at L4-5 also.

Reason for Exam: LOW BACK PAIN POST MVA PAIN RADIATING DOWN LT LEG PAIN IN THE GROIN AREA THIS IS WITH LIFTING RECETN MVA      ANY DISC LESION OR OTHER ETIOLOGY TO EXPLAIN PAIN      CLINICAL HISTORY: History provided of the low back pain post MVA. TECHNIQUE: Sagittal T1 and T2 sequences through the lumbar spine with axial T1 and T2 sequences from the mid L3 to mid S1 levels.     COMPARISON: No prior MRI available for direct comparison.     FINDINGS:     5 Lumbar type vertebral bodies are assumed.     Vertebral alignment is maintained apart from straightening of the normal lumbar lordosis. No scoliosis. Vertebral body heights are maintained. Marrow signal is normal.     Conus ends normally at L1 level. No focal intra or extra-axial abnormality. No abnormal cord signal.     No significant abnormality within the lower thoracic spine and upper lumbar spine.     At L1-2: Unremarkable. No significant spinal or foraminal stenosis.     At L2-3: Unremarkable. No significant spinal or foraminal stenosis.     At L3-4: Minimal disc degeneration with small posterior disc bulging. No significant spinal stenosis. Mild bilateral foraminal stenosis. Minimal left facet degenerative change.     At L4-5: Minimal disc degeneration with a small posterior disc bulging. Small left foraminal annular fissure. Facet joints are mildly hypertrophied. No significant spinal stenosis, however, there is mild narrowing of the lateral recesses. Mild bilateral foraminal stenosis.     At L5-S1: Minimal disc degeneration with small posterior disc bulging and left foraminal annular fissure. Mild facet degeneration. No significant spinal stenosis. Mild left foraminal stenosis. No right foraminal stenosis.     IMPRESSION:  Mild degenerative disease of the lower lumbar spine without spinal stenosis or severe foraminal narrowing.

No significant disc bulge, central canal stenosis, or foraminal stenosis  is demonstrated.       L1-L2: Minimal circumferential disc bulge is present.   No significant central canal or foraminal stenosis is demonstrated.       L2-L3: Schmorl's node involving the superior endplate of L3 is demonstrated in conjunction with a limbus vertebra   (developmental). No significant central canal stenosis is demonstrated.  However, the disc  abuts against the downward traversing L4 nerve roots within the lateral recesses raising the possibility of impingement upon the   structures.  There is mild bilateral foraminal stenosis.       L4-5: A moderate to large circumferential disc bulge is present.  Mild degenerative facet changes are present.  There is mild   prominence of the epidural fat suggestive of a component of epidural lipomatosis.  These findings result in moderate central canal  stenosis.  There is significant narrowing of the lateral recesses bilaterally with suspected impingement upon the downward   traversing L5 nerve roots.  There is severe right foraminal stenosis with possible compression of the exiting right L4 nerve root. At L5-S1, there  is suspected impingement upon the downward traversing S1 nerve roots within the lateral recesses.  There is severe bilateral   foraminal stenosis at L5-S1.

Reason for Exam: R LEG RADICULOPATHY; XRAY SHOWS LOSS OF DISC HEIGHT.   SCIATICA     Technique: Sagittal and axial T1 and T2 sequences of the lumbar spine were provided.     Findings:     Compared to plain films dated October 07, 2019.     The lowest fully formed vertebral body is labeled L5, and the conus is therefore normally positioned at the level of the L2 pedicles.  There is approximately 12 mm of anterior subluxation of L5 upon S1.  Alignment is otherwise unremarkable.  Vertebral body marrow signal is unremarkable in appearance, other than some degenerative endplate changes at L5-S1 level, as well as a suspected hemangioma within the T12 vertebra.     L1-2: Broad-based disc osteophyte complex resulting in mild spinal canal stenosis.  Neuroforamen remain patent bilaterally.  Mild disc space narrowing.     L2-3: Broad-based disc osteophyte complex eccentric to the left causing mild spinal canal stenosis.  Associated mild left-sided foraminal narrowing.  Disc spacing preserved.     L3-4: Mild broad-based disc osteophyte complex and facet joint hypertrophy contribute to mild spinal canal stenosis.  Associated mild narrowing of the left-sided neural foramen.  Mild disc space narrowing.     L4-5: Broad-based disc osteophyte complex and ligamentum flavum and facet joint hypertrophy contribute to mild spinal canal stenosis.  Associated mild narrowing of both neuroforamen.     L5-S1: Partial uncovering of the L5-S1 disc secondary to the described anterior subluxation of L5 upon S1.  Severe bilateral facet joint arthropathy, with both findings contributing to a moderate to severe degree of spinal canal stenosis and moderate to severe narrowing of the right-sided neural foramen which appears to compress the exiting right L5 nerve root.  Mild narrowing the left-sided neural foramen.  Partial effacement of both lateral recesses which may contribute to traversing S1 nerve root compromise.     There is a lesion of increased T2 signal within the posterior aspect of the right kidney measuring 1.7 cm, most consistent with a simple renal cyst.     Impression:     Multilevel degenerative changes, most pronounced at L5-S1 with significant anterior subluxation of L5 upon S1 secondary to severe facet joint arthropathy.  This results in narrowing of both neuroforamen, most pronounced on the right with suspected compression of the exiting right L5 nerve root.  There is also significant spinal canal compromise and narrowing of the lateral recesses which may compromise the traversing S1 nerve roots bilaterally.

Narrative & Impression  MR LUMBAR SPINE     Reason for Exam: PATIENT WITH VAGUE HISTORY. FROM OUT OF TOWN. STILL WAITING CHART TRANSFER. LOWER BACK WEDGE COMPRSSION WITH RED FLAGS++. WEAKNESS OF LEFT LOWER LIMB AND FECAL INCONTINENCE. ADVISED ER. PATIENT SAYS SLOWLY PROGRESSING. QUERY NERVE INVOLVMENT, POSSIBLE INFORMATION TO REFER URGENTLY TO ORTHOPEDIC SURGEON.     Compared to January 24, 2018 MRI     TECHNIQUE:     Sagittal and axial T1 and T2 weighted images of the lumbar spine.     FINDINGS:     For the purposes of this dictation, the lowest disc is labeled as S1-S2.     There remains curvature of the lumbar spine convex to the right. Lumbar vertebral body heights and alignment are otherwise preserved. Degenerative endplate changes are noted adjacent to the L4-5 and L5-S1. Marrow signal is otherwise grossly unremarkable. The visualized lower thoracic cord and conus are normal with the conus tip at L1.     At L2-3, minor broad-based disc bulge and minor facet degenerative changes are noted with no spinal or foraminal stenosis.     At L3-4, broad-based disc bulge mildly indents the ventral thecal sac. There is superimposed small left paracentral and medial foraminal disc protrusion which appears relatively stable. Mild facet degenerative change. There remains mild spinal canal stenosis.     At L4 -5, there is broad-based disc bulge indenting the ventral thecal sac. Mild to moderate facet degenerative changes remain stable. There is mild spinal canal stenosis and mild foraminal stenosis.     At L5-S1, minor broad-based disc bulge and posterior osteophytes. Minor facet degenerative change. No spinal canal stenosis. Given the prominent right eccentric disc osteophyte, there is moderate right foraminal stenosis.     IMPRESSION:     For the purposes of this dictation, the lowest disc is labeled as S1-S2 in keeping with lumbarization of S1.     Multilevel degenerative changes throughout the lumbar spine relatively stable from January 2018. Mild spinal canal stenosis is noted at L3-4 and L4-5 with no new large disc herniation or severe spinal canal stenosis.

HE HAS APPT FOR LUMBAR SPINE MRI ON OCTOBER 30, 2019 BECAUSE OF TINGLING AND NUMBNESS ALONG LT LEG     DISC PROTRUSION/PROLAPSE           ******** ADDENDUM #1 ********     The final paragraph of the IMPRESSION should say:     12 x 9 mm T2 hyperintense focus within the subcutaneous soft tissue of the neck on the left at the level of C6/7 may represent a sebaceous cyst.     ******** ORIGINAL REPORT ********  TECHNIQUE:  Sagittal T1, sagittal T2, and axial T2 medic imaging of the cervical spine was performed. L1-2: Broad-based disc osteophyte complex which does flatten the anterior thecal sac. Neuroforamen are patent bilaterally. Disc spacing preserved. L3-4: Broad-based disc osteophyte complex and ligament flavum hypertrophy contribute to moderate spinal canal stenosis with near complete effacement of CSF around the cauda equina nerve roots. Narrative & Impression  Technique:     T1-weighted, T2-weighted and inversion recovery sagittal and T1 and T2-weighted axial images of the lumbar spine were obtained.  Post intravenous gadolinium enhanced T1-weighted fat-saturated sagittal and T1-weighted without fat saturated axial images were then repeated.     FINDINGS:     History of the L5-S1 discectomy and L3-4 hemilaminectomies in the past.  Previous postoperative MRI of February 24, 2017 is also reviewed.     There appears to be a transitional vertebra and for the description purposes, the last well-formed disc space would be designated as L5-S1, like in the previous report.     The conus medullaris terminates at the T12-L1.  It remains normal.     The T12-L1, L1-L2 and L2-L3 discs demonstrate mild generalized bulge.  It seems that the pedicles at the L2-L3 are congenitally short and this is associated with moderately severe thickening of the ligamenta flava and mild hypertrophic degenerative osteoarthritis of facet joints.  As a combination of these changes, at least a moderate or moderate to marked spinal stenosis has occurred at this level.  Degree of the spinal stenosis has increased in the interval.  The spinal canal is normal at the T12-L1 and L1-L2.     At L3-L4, a marked degenerative disc disease is seen.  Bilateral decompression hemilaminectomies have been performed at this level.  The spinal canal demonstrate a normal caliber.  No residual or recurrent stenosis.  Neural foramina are also normal.  There is no appreciable enhancing scar tissue.     At L4-L5, a marked degenerative disc disease is seen.  This is associated with a mild generalized disc bulge and a small broad-based posterior central disc protrusion.  Degree of the disc protrusion, however, has slightly improved.  The ventral thecal sac is slightly compressed and the lateral recesses are also narrowed.  The bulged/protruded disc abuts against the bilateral descending L5 nerve roots in the lateral recesses.  Bilateral hemilaminectomies are also identified at the L4.  The spinal canal is of the normal caliber.  Neural foramina are also normal.     At L5-S1, a mild generalized at degenerative disc bulge is seen.  This is associated with a small broad-based posterior central disc protrusion with resultant slight compression of ventral thecal sac.  However, there is no neurological compromise.  The neural foramina are normal.  Lateral recesses are also normal on both sides.  There is no spinal canal stenosis.     OPINION:     1.  Normal postoperative changes at the L3-4 and L4-L5, as described above.  There is no residual or recurrent spinal canal stenosis.  Mild generalized at degenerative disc bulge and a small broad-based posterior central disc protrusion at the L4-L5.  The disc abuts against the bilateral descending L5 nerve roots in the lateral recesses.  This was also seen previously and has not significantly changed in the interval.  The degree of disc protrusion, however, has slightly improved.  2.  There is at least a moderate or moderate to marked spinal canal stenosis at the L2-L3 which has increased in the interval.

Narrative & Impression      ==== ORIGINAL REPORT ====        MRI cervical spine.      No prior imaging is available for comparison.      There is straightening of the cervical spine. No vertebral body compression fracture.      Visualized posterior fossa structures are unremarkable.      At C2-3 there are no significant degenerative changes. No neural compromise.      At C3-4 there is a posterior disc osteophyte complex with left paracentral-foraminal prominence. Moderate facet joint arthropathy. In combination there is mild spinal canal stenosis with focal impingement of the spinal cord. Inferior to the level of the disc a linear 0.9 cm focal area of cord signal increase is noted along the anterior cord. Severe left foraminal narrowing. No right foraminal narrowing.      At C4-5 shallow posterior disc osteophyte complex and mild facet joint arthropathy. Minimal indentation of the ventral cord but with no cord signal alteration. Moderate bilateral foraminal narrowing.      At C5-6 there is a posterior disc osteophyte complex with a focal left paracentral prominence. Right facet joint arthropathy. Within the subcutaneous tissues overlying the parasagittal left aspect of the lower cervical spine there is a noncomplex appearing encapsulated lesion measuring 4.6 cm x 1.4 cm x 3.3 cm. TECHNIQUE: MRI of the cervical spine was performed utilizing sagittal T1 and T2 sequences through the entire cervical spine, with axial medic 3-D T2 sequences from C2-C3 down to C7-T1.      FINDINGS: Comparison is made to the cervical spine x-rays from 28/2/2020.  Comparison is also made to the MRI of the cervical spine from 16/11/2011.      The cervical spine demonstrates a normal lordotic curvature and alignment.  Vertebral body heights are well-maintained.  Small amount of fatty endplate degenerative change at the C6-C7 level, which has developed from previous.  There is again an incidental tiny hemangioma within the T2 vertebral body.  No concerning bone lesions.      The prevertebral soft tissues are within normal limits.  The paraspinous musculature is grossly unremarkable.  Normal flow-voids within the bilateral vertebral arteries.  No evidence of lymphadenopathy.      The visualized portion of the brain parenchyma is within normal limits.  The cervical spinal cord demonstrates normal thickness/signal intensity.      Craniocervical junction: Unremarkable.      C2-C3: Unremarkable.      C3-C4: Unremarkable.      C4-C5: Unremarkable.      C5-C6: There are again tiny anterior osteophytes and a subtle diffuse disc bulge.  In the interval there has been development of mild to moderate left facet arthropathy.  These findings result in no significant spinal canal narrowing.  Minimal left neural foraminal narrowing, related to the facet arthropathy.      C6-C7: Worsening degenerative disc disease, with moderate loss of disc height, fatty endplate degenerative changes, anterior osteophytes, and loss of disc signal.  There is again a mild diffuse disc bulge.  There has been interval resolution of the right paracentral/foraminal disc protrusion.  There is now severe right uncovertebral hypertrophy, which is developed from previous.  There is a new small left paracentral/foraminal disc protrusion (sequence 2 images 9, 10, 11).  There is also new left uncovertebral hypertrophy, which is moderate in severity.  These findings result in moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal narrowing.  There is only partial effacement of the anterior and posterior CSF spaces, but no evidence of compression of the cord.      C7-T1: Tiny diffuse disc bulge, with no significant spinal canal/neural foraminal narrowing.      IMPRESSION:        ·       Worsening degenerative disc disease and uncovertebral hypertrophy at the C6-C7 level.  There has been interval resolution of the previously identified right paracentral/foraminal disc protrusion, but there is now a new small left paracentral/foraminal disc protrusion.  These findings collectively result in moderate to severe bilateral neural foraminal narrowing, which is worse than previous.          ·       Other findings as discussed.

Narrative & Impression  MR LUMBAR SPINE      Reason for Exam: POSSIBLE SPINAL STENOSIS, BACK PAIN WITH AGGRAVATION WITH WALKING, IMPPROVEMENT WITH LEANING FORWARD OVER SHOPPING CART. ALSO NOTES BALANCE AFFECTED     ?SPINAL STENOSIS     COMPARISON: Previous x-ray December 11/12 (Insight Spruce Grove).     TECHNIQUE: Routine non-augmented L-spine radiculopathy protocol.     FINDINGS:  5 lumbar type vertebral bodies are identified, as on prior plain radiograph. There is straightening of the lumbar spine. Minimal anterolisthesis of L3 on L4 by 2 mm (grade 1 severity) is noted, secondary to degenerative facet joint change at this level. Alignment of the lumbar spine is unchanged from previous.     T12-L1 demonstrates broad-based posterior disc bulge with a small posterior annular tear. Moderate degenerative facet joint changes are seen bilaterally. No significant stenosis is seen.     L1-2 demonstrates loss of disc height. Circumferential disc bulge with anterior and posterior osteophyte is noted. Moderate degenerative facet joint changes are seen bilaterally. Mild central spinal stenosis is seen. Moderate bilateral lateral recess stenoses are also identified, possibly affecting the traversing L2 nerve root on either side. Mild right foraminal stenosis is seen.     L2-3 demonstrates loss of disc height. Circumferential disc bulge with advanced degenerative facet joint changes seen. Anterior and posterior osteophyte is noted. Severe central and bilateral lateral recess stenoses result, possibly affecting the traversing L3 nerve root on either side. Mild right foraminal stenosis also seen.     L3-4 demonstrates advanced degenerative facet joint change bilaterally. There is resultant degenerative grade 1 anterolisthesis with posterior unroofing of the disc. Superimposed circumferential disc bulge is seen. This results in severe central and bilateral lateral recess stenoses. This possibly affects the traversing L4 nerve root on either side. Moderate right and mild left foraminal stenoses are also seen.     L4-5 demonstrates mild circumferential disc bulge. Mild degenerative facet joint changes seen bilaterally with some hypertrophy of the ligamentum flavum. No significant stenosis results at this level.     L5-S1 demonstrates minimal degenerative facet joint change bilaterally but is otherwise unremarkable. No significant stenosis seen.     IMPRESSION: Advanced multilevel degenerative change in the lumbar spine as described above. Severe central and bilateral lateral recess stenoses are seen from L1-2 down to L3-4.

Narrative & Impression  MR LUMBAR SPINE     Reason for Exam: CHRONIC LOW BACK PAIN, L SIDED SCIATICA.   DEVELOPED A FOOT DROP IN EARLY DEC 20219 - NOT RESOLVING WITH CONSERVATIVE MEANS.   MRI - SEP 2016 - SLIGHT NERVE ROOT IRRITATION OF L L5 NERVE ROOT.      HISTORY:  As above.     TECHNIQUE:  Standard radiculopathy protocol, consisting of sagittal T1 and T2 imaging from T11-12 to the mid sacrum and axial T1 and T2 imaging from L1-2 to L5-S1.     FINDINGS:  Comparison made to the MR lumbar spine from September 24, 2016 (UAH). Lumbar spine x-rays performed September 9, 2019 (Allin Clinic) were also reviewed.     Similar curvature of the lumbar spine convex left, centered at L2-3. Vertebral body heights are maintained. Small Schmorl's nodes within the endplates in the thoracolumbar spine. Marrow signal is unremarkable. No focal destructive osseous lesions.     Hypointense T2 disc signal noted within several of the discs, reflecting disc degeneration.     At T11-12, there is moderate loss of disc height. A small disc-osteophyte complex does not affect the conus or nerve roots. No spinal stenosis or neural foraminal stenosis.      At T12-L1, disc height is maintained. A small posterior disc-osteophyte complex does not affect the conus or nerve roots. No spinal stenosis or significant neural foraminal stenosis.     At L1-2, disc height is maintained. A small annular disc bulge does not cause any nerve root impingement. Slight narrowing of both neural foramina. No spinal stenosis. Minor facet degenerative changes.      At L2-3, disc height is maintained. A small annular disc bulge is present, with superimposed small far lateral disc protrusion on the left, encroaching upon the inferior aspect of the left neural foramen, abutting the exiting left L2 nerve root. Mild bilateral facet degenerative changes. No significant lateral recess stenosis or spinal stenosis. Mild stenosis of both neural foramina, more pronounced on the left. Appearances are unchanged.     At L3-4, there is mild loss of disc height eccentrically towards the right. A small posterior disc bulge indents the thecal sac. Mild bilateral facet degenerative changes with mild ligamentum flavum thickening. Slight narrowing of both lateral recesses and mild narrowing of the left neural foramen but no significant spinal stenosis. Appearances are not significantly changed.     At L4-5, there is new mild loss of disc height. New grade I spondylolisthesis of 4 mm noted, secondary to severe left-sided and moderate right-sided facet degeneration. The left-sided facet degeneration appears more severe, with osteophyte protruding anteromedially, encroaching upon the left lateral recess. A new, broad-based left paracentral/posterolateral disc extrusion is present, also encroaching upon the left lateral recess and proximal left neural foramen. As a result, there is now severe stenosis of the left lateral recess with compression of the descending left L5 nerve root. There may be impingement of the exiting left L4 nerve root also. Similar mild narrowing of the right lateral recess. New mild transverse narrowing of the thecal sac. More pronounced narrowing of the left neural foramen, now mild to moderate in severity. No significant stenosis of the right neural foramen.     At L5-S1, there is similar mild loss of disc height. A small shallow disc bulge indents the thecal sac. Bilateral facet degenerative changes of mild to moderate severity. No spinal stenosis, significant lateral recess narrowing nor neural foraminal stenosis. Appearances are not significantly changed.     Prevertebral soft tissues and visualized sacroiliac joints are unremarkable.     OPINION:  1. More pronounced disc degeneration at L4-5. New grade I spondylolisthesis at this level secondary to underlying bilateral (left greater than right) facet degeneration and hypertrophy. New severe stenosis of the left L4-5 lateral recess secondary to a combination of facet degeneration and new left-sided disc extrusion, with resultant compression of the descending left L5 nerve root and possible impingement of the exiting left L4 nerve root.     2. Degenerative disc disease within the remainder of the spine is of similar severity compared to the 2016 MR study.

At L2-3, disc height is well-maintained. There is diffuse hypointense T2 disc signal indicative of disc degeneration. Mild facet   degenerative changes. A small posterior disc bulge indents the ventral thecal sac. No focal nerve root impingement, spinal   stenosis or significant neural foraminal narrowing. Otherwise alignment is maintained.     Normal vertebral body heights.. No focal concerning bone lesion. Multilevel degenerative endplate signal change, with edematous features at L4-5.     At L1-2 there is mild disc degeneration and mild facet joint arthropathy. No spinal canal stenosis. No neural foraminal narrowing is noted.     At L2-3 there is a generalized posterior disc bulge and moderate facet joint arthropathy with ligamentum flavum overgrowth. No spinal canal stenosis centrally but mild narrowing of both lateral recesses is noted, this is similar to previous. Mild narrowing of the neural foramina.     At L3-4 there is disc degeneration with a generalized posterior disc bulge and moderate facet joint arthropathy with ligamentum flavum overgrowth. No spinal canal stenosis centrally. Moderate narrowing of both lateral recesses similar to marginally progressed since the prior examination. There is mild neural foraminal narrowing.     L4-5 there is disc degeneration with generalized posterior disc bulge. In addition there is a central-left paracentral inferior disc extrusion extending along the posterior aspect of the L5 vertebral body for approximately 2 cm. This extrusion is new since the prior examination and results in effacement of the left lateral recess, likely impinging upon the left L5 nerve. In addition focal moderately severe spinal canal stenosis is also noted. There is mild bilateral foraminal narrowing. Marked arthropathy of the facet joints with small volume fluid and bone overgrowth. Associated thickening of the ligamentum flavum.     At L5-S1 there is disc degeneration with a generalized posterior disc bulge and moderate facet joint arthropathy. Mild narrowing of the neural foramina.      No other significant degenerative change and/or spinal canal stenosis at any of the other levels.     Visualized retroperitoneum and the paravertebral musculature are unremarkable.        SUMMARY:  Multilevel degenerative changes involving the lumbar spine, as discussed above. At note at L4-5 there are progressive appearances with development of a new central and left paracentral inferior disc extrusion. This results in moderately severe focal spinal canal stenosis and effacement of the left lateral recess, likely impinging upon the left L5 nerve.     Other findings as discussed above.

MRI Lumbar spine     Technique:  Lumbar spine protocol  T1 and T2 sagittal  T1 and T2 transverse covering the L3-4 through to the L5-S1 disk spaces     Findings:     The conus medullaris is normally situated. At L4-5 the discs, thecal sac, intervertebral foramina, and exiting nerve roots appear normal.
